  "prompt": "How can I simplify [math]\\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}}+ \\frac{1}{1+x^{n-m}}?[/math]",
  "response": "To simplify the expression:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{1 + x^{m - n}} + \\frac{1}{1 + x^{n - m}}\n\\]\n\nLet's introduce a substitution to make the simplification easier. Let:\n\n\\[\ny = x^{m - n}\n\\]\n\nNotice that:\n\n\\[\nx^{n - m} = \\frac{1}{x^{m - n}} = \\frac{1}{y}\n\\]\n\nSubstituting these into the original expression gives:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{1 + y} + \\frac{1}{1 + \\frac{1}{y}} = \\frac{1}{1 + y} + \\frac{y}{1 + y}\n\\]\n\nNow, combine the two fractions:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1 + y}{1 + y} = 1\n\\]\n\nSo, the simplified form of the original expression is:\n\n\\[\n1\n\\]\n\n**Final Answer:**  \nAfter simplifying, the expression is equal to one.",
